<p>
<seg id=1> Meanwhile, in the China town area of Jakarta, the capital of Indonesia, Chinese and local people are defending their residences shoulder to shoulder. </seg>
<seg id=2> Since a serious riot in May, China town was violently attacked again. </seg>
<seg id=3> Please listen to another report by VOA correspondent Grand from Jakarta. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Curtain of night fell, soldiers were shooting to warn and dispel the young men gathered in China town and throwing stones to soldiers. </seg>
<seg id=5> Several hours ago, thousands of people in groups set fire and burned a bank only one kiloeter away from the President Palace. The raging fire spread quickly to nearby shops. </seg>
<seg id=6> These young people broke the door of a shop by a road lamp pillar. </seg>
<seg id=7> In their attack to Chinese in Saturday, a herd of people pulled a Chinese to street, beat him, and threw him into a water channel. </seg>
<seg id=8> Then the army drove an armored personnel carrier to save this badly wounded person. </seg>
<seg id=9> Tanks were patrolling on the streets full of stones and broken glasses, thousands of soldiers, with guns and tear bombs, were watching the local commercial area and kept the riots away from here. </seg>
<seg id=10> After the chaos in May, the businessman who managed electrical products was forced to move his shop. </seg>
<seg id=11> The reporter saw a young man of 29, whose surname was Min, was watching behind a wire netting roadblock, just with his pants and leather belt. </seg>
<seg id=12> This young man, who was working in a computer company, said that he and his Islamic neighbors would guard against the riots for the whole night to prevent robbery. </seg>
<seg id=13> Mr. Min said after the chaos in May, his neighbor built this wire netting roadblock. But he had never thought to use them so soon. </seg>
<seg id=14> In some road-blocked area, the local dwellers dispelled groups of strangers with their big wooden sticks. </seg>
<seg id=15> A resident named Daseyat, with a Muslim hat and a Muslim sarong on him, </seg>
<seg id=16> said to reporter that most of those robbing young men came from other places out of China town when they heard the disturbance here. </seg>
<seg id=17> These mobs robbed and destroyed an underground railway station one kilometer away. Being chased after by the soldiers, the mobs threw away shoes, computers, and clothing shelves all the road. </seg>
</p>
